=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Real Madrid paid a record euro77m ($66m) for Zinedine Zidane, a=
 French=20
international. The Spanish football club financed the deal and paid off deb=
ts=20
by selling its training complex in Madrid=01,s business district.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Opposite banks
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09As expected, the British government blocked an o18 billion ($25=
 billion) bid=20
by Lloyds TSB for Abbey National on competition grounds. This will, in=20
effect, put an end to consolidation among Britain=01,s big banks; they may =
now=20
seek targets abroad.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09See article: Ellwood Agonistes=20
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09CSFB, a Wall Street bank under regulatory investigation for its=
 handling of=20
initial public offerings, ousted its chief executive, Allen Wheat. He will =
be=20
replaced by John Mack, former president of Morgan Stanley.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Euronext, the outcome of a merger of bourses in Amsterdam, Brus=
sels and=20
Paris, made a poor showing on its own stockmarket debut. Its shares, traded=
=20
on all three exchanges, fell by 8.5% on the first day despite being priced =
at=20
the low end of the range.=20
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Merrill Lynch, America=01,s largest stockbroker, sought to reas=
sure sceptical=20
customers of the impartiality of its analysts by stopping them owning share=
s=20
in companies that they cover.=20
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09FTSE International, a British stockmarket indexer, launched FTS=
E4Good, a set=20
of stockmarket indices for socially responsible investment. Many of Britain=
=01,s=20
top companies failed to make the grade.
